##Introduction
On Day3, I focused on interpreting the FastQC report generated from the FASTQ file. The session helped me understand how to evaluate sequencing data quality using different graphs and summary metrics.

##Tool Used
FastQC (quality control tool for sequencing data)

##FastQC Report Interpretation
The FastQC report contains multiple modules, each representing a quality parameter:
- Basic Statistics
Provides general information such as file name, total sequences, sequence length, and GC content.
- Per Base Sequence Quality
Shows quality scores across all bases. High-quality scores (green region) indicate good sequencing quality.
- Per Sequence Quality Scores
Displays overall quality distribution of reads.
- Per Base Sequence Content
Shows proportion of A, T, G, C across positions. Ideally, lines should be balanced.
- Per Sequence GC Content
Indicates GC distribution. Deviations may suggest contamination.
- Sequence Length Distribution
Shows variation in read lengths.
- Sequence Duplication Levels
Identifies duplicate sequences, which may indicate PCR bias.
- Overrepresented Sequences
Highlights sequences that appear frequently (possible contamination or adapters).
- Adapter Content
Detects presence of adapter sequences.

##Observations
Some modules showed pass (green) indicating good quality
Some showed warning (orange) or fail (red) indicating potential issues
Quality was generally good, but certain parameters may require preprocessing (like trimming)

##Conclusion
This session helped me understand how to interpret FastQC graphs and identify quality issues in sequencing data. This step is important before further analysis like alignment or assembly.
